04742nam a22007455i 9789814517935DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015si     fo  d z      eng d  a2015322703  a97898145179357 a10.1355/97898145179352doi  a(DE-B1597)492535  a(OCoLC)947228778  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG00aQC903.2.B37bC43 2015 4aQC903.2.B37bC43 2015 7aNAT0110002bisacsh04a304.25098412231 aChaturvedi, Sanjay, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aClimate Change and the Bay of Bengal :bEvolving Geographies of Fear and Hope /cSanjay Chaturvedi, Vijay Sakhuja. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (252 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- t1. Geopolitics in the Era of Climate Change: Rethinking Sovereignty, Security and Sust -- t2. Mapping the Bay of Bengal in the Era of Climate Change -- t3. Climate Change, Displacements and Imperatives of 62 Human Security -- t4. Strategic Responses to Non-traditional Security Threats: The Role of the Military -- t5. Rescaling the ‘National’: Realities, Perceptions and Policies -- t6. Assessing Regional Responses: A Case for Reorientation -- t7. Conclusion: Towards a Bay of Bengal Community -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tABOUT THE AUTHORS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aClimate Change and the Bay of Bengal argues that in the era of climate change radically different understandings of security and sovereignty are at work. It questions the geopolitics of fear and the manner in which metanarratives of climate change tend to privilege the “global” and “national” scales over other scales, especially the regional and the local. The authors argue in favour of a new imagination of the Bay of Bengal space as a semi-enclosed sea, embedded in a large marine ecosystem, under the relevant provisions of the UNCLOS that impose various obligations upon its signatories to cooperate at a regional level. Such an imagination, anchored in geographies of hope, should not remain confined to official domains and discourses but become a part of popular socio-spatial consciousness through a regional public diplomacy reaching out to the grassroots level. A Bay of Bengal regional seas programme, under the auspices of UNEP, should be conceptualized and operationalized in a manner that explicitly factors in climate change consequences into the existing understandings and approaches to environmental-human security in the region.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aClimatic changeszBengal, Bay of. 0aClimatic changes. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh1 aSakhuja, Vijay, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066300608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017z978311060667608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPP Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070099240uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981451793540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789814517935423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789814517935.jpg  a978-3-11-060667-6  ISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017c2015d2017  a978-3-11-066300-6  ISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-070099-2  PP Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5